-- в”Ђв”Ђ Arista в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Arista Networks is a publicly traded cloud networking company that designs high-performance data center switches and its EOS network operating system.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$custom$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE(NULL, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2004, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$approx 4,850 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Santa Clara, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Arista Networks 2026: EOS Switches and Company Overview$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Arista Networks (NYSE: ANET) builds cloud data center switches and the EOS network operating system. See company history, scale, and core products.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Arista Networks is a publicly traded networking hardware and software company (NYSE: ANET) headquartered in Santa Clara, California, that designs and sells high-performance switches and routers for cloud data centers, enterprise campuses, and AI networking infrastructure. The company was founded in 2004 (initially under the name Arastra) by Andy Bechtolsheim, a Sun Microsystems co-founder and prolific Silicon Valley investor and engineer, along with David Cheriton and Kenneth Duda; it was renamed Arista Networks in 2008. Arista has long been led by CEO Jayshree Ullal, a former senior Cisco executive, and the company went public via IPO in 2014. Arista's core technology is EOS, the Extensible Operating System, a Linux-based, fully programmable, modular network operating system that runs as a single software image across Arista's entire switching product line, giving customers a consistent operating environment from the data center core to the network edge. The company built its business primarily around merchant-silicon switches for cloud titans and large enterprises, positioning itself as a leaner, software-centric alternative to legacy networking vendors, most notably Cisco. Arista has grown into a large-scale public company: it surpassed 2 billion dollars in quarterly revenue for the first time in Q1 2025, reported roughly 2.2 billion dollars in revenue for Q2 2025, and achieved a record 7 billion dollars in full-year revenue for fiscal 2024, with continued growth since. As of late 2025, the company employed approximately 4,857 people worldwide. Arista's product portfolio spans cloud networking switches and routers, campus networking equipment, network security and monitoring products (following its CloudVision management platform and various acquisitions), and increasingly AI-focused networking infrastructure to support large-scale GPU clusters and AI data centers. Its customers include major cloud service providers, large enterprises, and financial services and high-frequency trading firms that require low-latency, high-throughput networking. Because Arista sells enterprise hardware and software through a direct sales and channel partner model, pricing is custom and quote-based rather than published in fixed tiers, typically involving significant capital investment scaled to a customer's data center or campus deployment size. As a mature, large-cap public company, Arista is not a typical SaaS or software directory listing in the startup sense, but it remains a significant player that SEO-relevant buyers research when evaluating enterprise networking infrastructure and Cisco alternatives.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '49f3b309-4a25-4b5f-8510-8a8e1a3e50bb';

