-- в”Ђв”Ђ ArrowDL в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$ArrowDL is a free, open-source, cross-platform download manager that lets users batch download, queue, and organize files, media, and torrents.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$open-source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE(NULL, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$ArrowDL 2026: Free Open-Source Download Manager$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$ArrowDL is a free, open-source download manager for Windows, macOS, and Linux with batch downloads, queue management, and browser integration.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$ArrowDL, also known as Arrow Downloader, is a free and open-source download manager application for Windows, macOS, and Linux, distributed at arrow-dl.com and developed on GitHub under the setvisible/ArrowDL repository. It is written in C++ using the Qt application framework and is released under the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL), making it free to use, inspect, and modify. ArrowDL is designed as a standalone application with its own embedded web engine, meaning it does not depend on a third-party web browser to capture or manage downloads, though it also offers browser extensions for Firefox and Chromium-based browsers (available on the Chrome Web Store and Firefox add-ons site) that send links from the browser to the standalone ArrowDL application. The core use case for ArrowDL is batch and mass downloading: it lets users collect and queue large numbers of links, images, music files, documents, and other files found on the web, including content from video-sharing sites and peer-to-peer or BitTorrent sources, and download them in an organized, prioritized queue rather than one at a time. Users can pause, resume, and stop individual downloads or the entire queue, reprioritize items, and have ArrowDL automatically recreate the same subdirectory structure found on the source web page when saving files locally. Additional organizational features include batch renaming and batch moving of downloaded items, making it easier to manage large download sets after the fact. Because it is free, open source, and has no company or commercial pricing behind it, ArrowDL is best compared to other free download manager utilities such as JDownloader, Free Download Manager, or built-in browser download managers, rather than to commercial cloud-based file transfer or content delivery products. Its target audience is everyday users and power users who regularly download large batches of files, images, or media from the web and want more control, organization, and reliability (via pause/resume and queue management) than a browser's default download handling provides.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '05511d22-956f-4717-b903-1a7fa4fc130e';

